00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:50.320
that we know is tested the best.

00:39:51.670 --> 00:39:54.385
AUDIENCE: You provided a number
of examples about big things

00:39:54.385 --> 00:39:55.010
that were done.

00:39:56.380 --> 00:39:58.310
Affecting a lot of people.

00:39:58.310 --> 00:40:01.070
Taxpayers, guests in hotels.

00:40:01.070 --> 00:40:02.820
Do you have examples
of things that you've

00:40:02.820 --> 00:40:05.970
done for one on one
interactions with other people

00:40:05.970 --> 00:40:08.010
where this comes into play?

00:40:08.010 --> 00:40:08.900
STEVE: Yeah.

00:40:08.900 --> 00:40:11.880
Yeah, let me give you a couple
of those, because, yeah, I

00:40:11.880 --> 00:40:15.220
think when we're talking
about these big data sets,

00:40:15.220 --> 00:40:16.990
large numbers of
homogeneous transactions

00:40:16.990 --> 00:40:19.364
allow us to be able to present
a compelling case in terms

00:40:19.364 --> 00:40:21.040
of the robustness.

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:23.170
But oftentimes our
influence appeals

00:40:23.170 --> 00:40:26.470
are simply down to a
one to one interaction

00:40:26.470 --> 00:40:29.190
with a colleague or a manager.

00:40:29.190 --> 00:40:31.530
So let me give you a couple.

00:40:31.530 --> 00:40:34.230
There's one that actually
we talk about in the book.

00:40:34.230 --> 00:40:38.800
A series of studies conducted
by Terri Kurtzberg from Rutgers

00:40:38.800 --> 00:40:40.866
University over
in New Jersey, who

00:40:40.866 --> 00:40:42.490
finds that when we
are looking to build

00:40:42.490 --> 00:40:44.840
a relationship with
someone who is remote

00:40:44.840 --> 00:40:48.720
to us, a colleague perhaps
in a different city

00:40:48.720 --> 00:40:52.280
or even in a different region
of the world, something

00:40:52.280 --> 00:40:54.980
we can do very, very early
on in our email exchanges

00:40:54.980 --> 00:40:59.900
to humanize that
interaction is to place

00:40:59.900 --> 00:41:02.780
an attachment, such
a small cartoon.

00:41:03.810 --> 00:41:06.740
So she conducted this with
one to one negotiations

00:41:06.740 --> 00:41:11.010
in organizations and found that
when the individual concerned

00:41:11.010 --> 00:41:15.510
reached out to a negotiating
partner in their organization--

00:41:15.510 --> 00:41:18.230
and in this instance, actually
attached a Dilbert cartoon,

00:41:18.230 --> 00:41:21.220
where Dilbert actually screws
up a negotiation-- that

00:41:21.220 --> 00:41:23.570
was the kind of ice breaker.

00:41:23.570 --> 00:41:28.750
So in an increasingly electronic
world we actually live in,

00:41:28.750 --> 00:41:31.680
these small steps that just
humanize an interaction

00:41:31.680 --> 00:41:37.826
could be important things that
make the difference to everyone

00:41:37.826 --> 00:41:39.950
else that's doing the quick,
efficient email thing.

00:41:39.950 --> 00:41:42.680
So there is an immediate
example in a one to one

00:41:42.680 --> 00:41:44.300
situation reaching
out to colleagues.

00:41:44.300 --> 00:41:46.591
AUDIENCE: So that's an example
of changing the context.

00:41:47.282 --> 00:41:48.240
STEVE: Yes, I think so.

00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:48.880
Yeah, yeah.

00:41:48.880 --> 00:41:54.910
It gives a sense of there's
someone on the other side,

00:41:54.910 --> 00:41:57.140
not just perhaps a
faceless email address.

00:41:57.140 --> 00:41:58.630
It humanizes that interaction.

00:41:59.680 --> 00:42:02.710
AUDIENCE: How can you guard
against these techniques being

00:42:02.710 --> 00:42:03.370
used on you?

00:42:03.370 --> 00:42:05.200
Because sometimes I
mean, these techniques

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:07.200
can be used in a good way
and also in a bad way.

00:42:07.200 --> 00:42:11.310
So is it like just by knowing
these techniques it-selves,

00:42:11.310 --> 00:42:13.590
is it enough to
guard against them?

00:42:14.780 --> 00:42:16.760
STEVE: Yeah, I mean
that's a great question.

00:42:18.090 --> 00:42:21.240
In fact, there's an inherent
message underneath that

00:42:21.240 --> 00:42:24.580
as well, which is that
some of these effects

00:42:24.580 --> 00:42:28.920
can be used to exploit, to
manipulate, to get people

00:42:28.920 --> 00:42:31.900
perhaps to make decisions
that they wouldn't ordinarily

00:42:31.900 --> 00:42:34.502
make if they had all the
facts or all the information

00:42:34.502 --> 00:42:35.210
to actually have.

00:42:35.210 --> 00:42:39.130
So there's a very important
ethical message here.

00:42:39.130 --> 00:42:42.560
That one would hope that you'd
only use these in a morally,

00:42:42.560 --> 00:42:43.990
responsible, and ethical way.

00:42:45.380 --> 00:42:49.190
I think that understanding
these biases,

00:42:49.190 --> 00:42:52.380
understanding how they do affect
and influence us can help.

00:42:53.840 --> 00:42:58.100
So one could make the argument
that any book about influence

00:42:58.100 --> 00:43:00.990
and persuasion, or any set of
information about the influence

00:43:00.990 --> 00:43:04.320
and persuasion process is
not only a set of tools

00:43:04.320 --> 00:43:05.860
to influence and
persuade others,

00:43:05.860 --> 00:43:08.790
but arguably could be used as
a defense strategy as well.

00:43:10.480 --> 00:43:15.360
I'm not entirely convinced
that knowing these effects

00:43:15.360 --> 00:43:16.330
is going to be enough.

00:43:17.400 --> 00:43:19.890
And the primary reason
for that is that we just

00:43:19.890 --> 00:43:25.210
don't have oftentimes
the space to think about

00:43:25.210 --> 00:43:26.970
whether they are
being used on us.

00:43:26.970 --> 00:43:30.510
And I'm particularly
these small changes

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:34.250
that are so small they
often fly under the radar.

00:43:34.250 --> 00:43:38.284
There is very good evidence
from the persuasion sciences

00:43:38.284 --> 00:43:39.950
and behavioral sciences,
more generally,

00:43:39.950 --> 00:43:43.670
that people aren't that
good at recognizing

00:43:43.670 --> 00:43:46.100
what it is in a context that
does influence and persuade

00:43:46.100 --> 00:43:46.600
them.

00:43:46.600 --> 00:43:47.950
There's a really
great set of studies

00:43:47.950 --> 00:43:49.575
that were conducted
here in California.

00:43:50.750 --> 00:43:52.200
When researchers
went door to door

00:43:52.200 --> 00:43:55.690
asking homeowners which
message would most

00:43:55.690 --> 00:43:58.100
motivate them to reduce
their energy consumption.

00:43:58.100 --> 00:44:01.270
Perhaps be a little bit more
environmentally friendly.

00:44:01.270 --> 00:44:07.310
They rated information about how
if they change their behavior

00:44:07.310 --> 00:44:10.350
it would be
beneficial to society

00:44:10.350 --> 00:44:12.390
as the biggest
motivation, followed

00:44:12.390 --> 00:44:15.390
by the impact of having
future generations,

00:44:15.390 --> 00:44:17.730
followed by the savings
they'd actually make.

00:44:17.730 --> 00:44:20.060
They dismissed the idea
that because their neighbors

00:44:20.060 --> 00:44:22.080
were increasingly
making these changes

00:44:22.080 --> 00:44:24.080
that it would have
any influence.

00:44:24.080 --> 00:44:27.170
But then, in the tests,
when those messages

00:44:27.170 --> 00:44:30.090
were distributed across the
neighbors, the neighborhoods

00:44:30.090 --> 00:44:32.934
rather, that message
of social proof

00:44:32.934 --> 00:44:34.600
was the only message
that had an effect.

00:44:34.600 --> 00:44:38.250
So it's a really good
demonstration of much

00:44:38.250 --> 00:44:42.240
as it might not be
comforting to learn,

00:44:42.240 --> 00:44:43.980
we often aren't that
good at recognizing

00:44:43.980 --> 00:44:45.480
what does influence
and persuade us.

00:44:45.480 --> 00:44:47.520
So I'm not entirely
convinced that

00:44:47.520 --> 00:44:49.820
just learning about
them will be enough.

00:44:49.820 --> 00:44:51.352
But I think it's a good step.

00:44:51.352 --> 00:44:53.060
AUDIENCE: More and
more I think about it,

00:44:53.060 --> 00:44:55.680
my takeaway is that
you don't really

00:44:55.680 --> 00:44:58.190
know what is actually
going to work.

00:44:58.190 --> 00:45:02.150
And it depends on the context,
depends on the people.

00:45:02.150 --> 00:45:06.060
The same message may not
work in a different crowd.

00:45:06.060 --> 00:45:11.260
So if you just had one chance,
then almost, you could try,

00:45:11.260 --> 00:45:13.750
but you don't know what
the effect is going to be.

00:45:13.750 --> 00:45:16.630
But if you were able
to do some testing,

00:45:16.630 --> 00:45:19.370
and so on, and try
different options then

00:45:19.370 --> 00:45:22.510
you have a possibility
like the AB testing

00:45:22.510 --> 00:45:26.190
where you could do 1%, 2%, and
then go for a larger message.

00:45:26.190 --> 00:45:29.270
But like the presentations
and so on, you have one shot.

00:45:29.270 --> 00:45:32.690
Where you're talking to a VP and
saying, hey, here's the thing.

00:45:32.690 --> 00:45:35.170
You could deploy the strategy
which you talked about,

00:45:35.170 --> 00:45:36.900
hey, use two of these.

00:45:36.900 --> 00:45:38.750
You don't really
know what the effect

00:45:38.750 --> 00:45:40.010
is going to be ultimately.

00:45:40.010 --> 00:45:43.250
STEVE: Well, I do except
that to a certain point.

00:45:43.250 --> 00:45:46.720
However, I do
think that there is

00:45:46.720 --> 00:45:48.860
a huge advantage
to understanding

00:45:48.860 --> 00:45:51.922
the fundamental principles
compared to perhaps just going

00:45:51.922 --> 00:45:52.630
with gut feeling.

00:45:53.820 --> 00:45:54.350
Yeah?

00:45:54.350 --> 00:45:59.170
And if we know that
we can increase

00:45:59.170 --> 00:46:03.270
the appeal, the effectiveness
of our proposition,

00:46:03.270 --> 00:46:07.480
by aligning it to one or more
of these core motivations,

00:46:07.480 --> 00:46:09.390
and that we will be
in a better position

00:46:09.390 --> 00:46:16.390
than not, that alone has
got to be of huge value

00:46:16.390 --> 00:46:21.630
compared to sitting at our desks
with the spreadsheet in front

00:46:21.630 --> 00:46:23.720
of us, the slideshow,
whatever it may be,

00:46:23.720 --> 00:46:26.670
thinking about, well, what do
I think will influence this VP?

00:46:27.690 --> 00:46:32.850
There's a set of tools
grounded in good evidence that

00:46:32.850 --> 00:46:36.100
will increase potentially
the likelihood that we

00:46:36.100 --> 00:46:37.010
will be successful.

00:46:37.010 --> 00:46:41.660
I'm never going to say, and any
person that comes into Google

00:46:41.660 --> 00:46:44.990
and says that they found the
way to persuade 100% of people

00:46:44.990 --> 00:46:47.340
100% of the time, you want
to kick them out the door.

00:46:47.340 --> 00:46:48.750
Because it doesn't exist.

00:46:48.750 --> 00:46:52.250
But we can, by making
these small changes,

00:46:52.250 --> 00:46:55.230
measure bigger affects in
our persuasive success.

00:46:55.230 --> 00:46:56.601
There's no doubt about that.

00:46:56.601 --> 00:46:59.100
AUDIENCE: Got a question on
just more personal as far as you

00:46:59.100 --> 00:47:00.340
writing this book.

00:47:00.340 --> 00:47:01.850
What was your
process involved in

00:47:01.850 --> 00:47:03.850
like finding time for
yourself to get this done?

00:47:05.740 --> 00:47:06.696
STEVE: Yeah.

00:47:06.696 --> 00:47:08.570
And there's three of
us, by the way, as well.

00:47:08.570 --> 00:47:10.674
It's not just my book.

00:47:10.674 --> 00:47:12.090
Noah Goldstein and
Robert Cialdini

00:47:12.090 --> 00:47:13.750
have also contributed equally.

00:47:16.630 --> 00:47:21.380
So one thing that has
helped is the fact

00:47:21.380 --> 00:47:24.670
that we've structured this
book slightly differently

00:47:24.670 --> 00:47:26.780
to a traditional book,
which would have maybe

00:47:26.780 --> 00:47:29.360
a core idea and then
eight or nine chapters

00:47:29.360 --> 00:47:30.590
that it expands on.

00:47:30.590 --> 00:47:35.010
This book is made up of
actually 53 chapters,

00:47:35.010 --> 00:47:40.070
and each chapter is no
more than 1,500 words long.

00:47:40.070 --> 00:47:44.150
So it presents an insight
from persuasion science,

00:47:44.150 --> 00:47:46.880
it gives you enough of
the underlying mechanism

00:47:46.880 --> 00:47:50.400
to get in touch with
what's actually going on,

00:47:50.400 --> 00:47:52.430
and then it rapidly
moves to a, here's

00:47:52.430 --> 00:47:54.740
what it means to you
at work, at home,

00:47:54.740 --> 00:47:55.990
whatever the situation may be.

00:47:58.020 --> 00:48:02.330
And so writing them
in that way, I think,

00:48:02.330 --> 00:48:04.670
was a good exercise,
because we could write them

00:48:04.670 --> 00:48:07.720
as perhaps blog
posts to begin with.

00:48:07.720 --> 00:48:10.200
500 or 600 word blog posts.

00:48:10.200 --> 00:48:15.560
Scan the latest research, read
the abstracts in the journals,

00:48:15.560 --> 00:48:20.599
pick those that we think have
a good basis of application,

00:48:20.599 --> 00:48:21.890
and then extend those chapters.

00:48:21.890 --> 00:48:25.260
So we could write them
at different times.

00:48:25.260 --> 00:48:28.630
And we don't necessarily have
to write them sequentially,

00:48:28.630 --> 00:48:29.520
one after the other.

00:48:29.520 --> 00:48:34.879
We could write them as the
data becomes available,

00:48:34.879 --> 00:48:36.420
and then think about
the application.

00:48:36.420 --> 00:48:38.620
So that's one of the
approaches we actually made,

00:48:38.620 --> 00:48:41.250
and that made the
job a lot easier.

00:48:42.161 --> 00:48:43.910
Of course, the challenge
then is just when

00:48:43.910 --> 00:48:45.460
you've got lots
and lots of content

00:48:45.460 --> 00:48:47.890
is how you actually organize it.

00:48:47.890 --> 00:48:50.690
And that's where this idea of
these three core motivations

00:48:50.690 --> 00:48:51.190
came in.

00:48:51.190 --> 00:48:53.060
That we could generally
categorized them.

00:48:54.002 --> 00:48:55.710
And that's the approach
we actually took.

00:48:57.070 --> 00:48:58.890
I think the final
thing which was useful,

00:48:58.890 --> 00:49:01.990
was the fact that-- so I'm
not an academic by training.

00:49:01.990 --> 00:49:03.930
My two colleagues clearly are.

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:09.380
And so to have that balance of
scientifically and academically

00:49:09.380 --> 00:49:12.340
informed insights, but
then a reality check

00:49:12.340 --> 00:49:14.730
that said, OK, well, that's
all very well in theory,

00:49:14.730 --> 00:49:16.190
but how do you
apply in practice?

00:49:16.190 --> 00:49:20.670
What does that mean to people in
Google, people in organizations

00:49:20.670 --> 00:49:22.610
that need to interact
each and every day?

00:49:22.610 --> 00:49:24.240
How do we operationalize this?

00:49:24.240 --> 00:49:26.150
I think that was also
an important aspect

00:49:26.150 --> 00:49:29.030
of the creation process too.

00:49:29.030 --> 00:49:31.250
Well, thank you
very much indeed.

00:49:31.250 --> 00:49:34.600
[APPLAUSE]

